+---
+title: Execution patterns
+description: How queue-level execution patterns (static-dag, pipeline, map-reduce) layer above the engine tick, how the gate/respawn circle-back works, the extendRun + run.extended audit seam, and the forward-arc-never-rewind invariant that keeps every run graph acyclic.
+---
+
+The core orchestrator engine — ticks, `depends_on` resolution, resource locks,
+fire-and-reconcile — knows nothing about *what shape* a run should have. It
+schedules items; it does not decide whether more items should exist. **Execution
+patterns** fill that gap. A pattern is a per-queue strategy object that sits
+*above* the engine: after each engine tick the orchestrator runs a **pattern
+phase** that may decide to extend the run with new items, and those items flow
+right back into the unchanged engine on the next tick.
+
+This page explains the three built-in patterns, how you configure them on a
+queue, the `extendRun` seam and its audit trail, and the invariant that keeps
+every dynamically grown run graph correct.
+
+For the engine tick mechanics that patterns build on, see
+[How an offload run executes](/pangolin/explanation/how-offload-runs/). For the run
+graph format that `extendRun` validates against, see the
+[plan.json reference](/pangolin/reference/plan-json/).
+
+## The three patterns
+
+Each pattern is a pure function: given the current terminal items of a run, it
+either returns a spawn directive (new items + edges) or returns nothing. Patterns
+keep no state of their own; all state lives in the run graph that the engine
+already manages.
+
+### `static-dag`
+
+The default. No pattern phase runs at all — the run's item set is fixed at
+submit time, and the engine works through it to completion. Use this whenever
+you know the full work graph up front. It is the simplest and most predictable
+shape: audit trail, provenance closure, and retry semantics are fully determined
+before a single item fires.
+
+### `pipeline`
+
+A `pipeline` run is a sequence of **stages** declared on the queue. Each stage
+is a named executor with optional gate logic. The pattern phase fires after each
+stage's items complete:
+
+1. It examines the terminal items of the stage that just finished.
+2. If a **gate** item is present and passed, the pattern emits the next stage's
+   items as a spawn directive — the run grows forward by one stage.
+3. If the gate failed (or no gate is configured and any item failed), the
+   pattern may emit a **respawn**: a corrective item or mini-DAG appended to the
+   *same run*, with `depends_on` pointing at the failed stage's items. On the
+   next tick those new items enter the engine as ordinary `pending` items.
+4. If the respawn itself terminates successfully, the pattern re-examines from
+   the gating stage — the pipeline advances only after a clean pass.
+
+The circle-back is not a literal cycle in the graph. The failed stage items
+remain as sealed history. The corrective items are new nodes appended *after*
+them; they are what "circle back" semantically, but the graph edge always points
+from new → old, never old → new. The invariant (below) explains why this must be
+so.
+
+### `map-reduce`
+
+A `map-reduce` run begins with a **splitter** item whose output lists the keys
+to fan over (file paths, shard ids, any opaque strings the splitter writes to
+`outputs/`). The pattern phase fires once the splitter is `done`:
+
+1. It reads the splitter's `resultRef`, fetches the output manifest, and emits
+   one map item per key — all with `depends_on: [<splitterItemId>]`.
+2. After all map items are `done`, it emits a single reduce item with
+   `depends_on` pointing at every map item.
+
+The fan-out width is unknown at submit time — that is the whole point. You
+submit a run with just the splitter, and the pattern grows it to N+1 items once
+the splitter has counted N. The engine never needed to know N; it just schedules
+whatever items exist on each tick.
+
+## Queue-level pattern config
+
+Patterns are attached to queues, not to individual runs. A run submitted to a
+pattern-bound queue automatically participates in its pattern's phase; there is
+no per-run opt-in. Configure the pattern in your `pangolin.config` under the queue
+definition:
+
+```ts
+queues: [
+  {
+    name: 'pipeline-q',
+    concurrency: 2,
+    pattern: {
+      type: 'pipeline',
+      stages: [
+        { name: 'lint',    executor: 'lint-executor' },
+        { name: 'test',    executor: 'test-executor',  gate: 'gate-test' },
+        { name: 'deploy',  executor: 'deploy-executor' },
+      ],
+      maxRespawns: 3,
+    },
+  },
+  {
+    name: 'fanout-q',
+    concurrency: 8,
+    pattern: {
+      type: 'map-reduce',
+      splitterExecutor: 'file-splitter',
+      mapExecutor:      'file-processor',
+      reduceExecutor:   'aggregator',
+    },
+  },
+]
+```
+
+A queue with no `pattern` key uses `static-dag` implicitly. The `concurrency`
+budget and `resourceLocks` semantics are unchanged regardless of pattern — the
+pattern phase only decides *which items exist*; the engine decides *which of
+those items run at once*.
+
+The pattern phase runs **after** the engine tick and **before** the seal check.
+A run that was just extended structurally cannot seal on that same tick, because
+the newly spawned items enter as `pending` and are therefore not terminal. The
+seal check sees live items and correctly defers.
+
+## `extendRun` and `run.extended` audit entries
+
+The pattern phase never writes items directly into the run-state store. All
+spawns flow through the audited **`extendRun`** seam:
+
+1. The pattern returns a `SpawnDirective` — a partial plan fragment: new item
+   descriptors and their `depends_on` edges.
+2. `extendRun` merges the fragment into the existing run graph and validates the
+   result through the same `validateRun` called at submit time. An invalid
+   fragment (unknown executor, duplicate id, forward edge) is rejected and logged
+   as an error; the run continues without the bad spawn.
+3. On success, every new item is written to the run-state store with `status:
+   pending` and attributed to the actor `pattern:<queueName>` rather than to the
+   original submitter.
+4. An audit entry of type **`run.extended`** is appended, naming:
+   - the run id,
+   - the pattern type and queue,
+   - the **cause item** — the terminal item whose completion triggered this
+     spawn,
+   - the ids of every newly added item.
+
+```
+{ type: "run.extended",
+  runId: "r-abc123",
+  pattern: "pipeline",
+  queue: "pipeline-q",
+  causeItemId: "gate-test",
+  spawnedIds: ["deploy-1"],
+  actor: "pattern:pipeline-q",
+  ts: "2026-06-04T09:12:03.441Z" }
+```
+
+Spawn ids are **deterministic**: `<runId>/<causeItemId>/<sequenceN>`. Because
+`extendRun` skips already-present ids, a crash-and-rescan re-derives the same
+directive and applies it as a no-op. The audit entry is then also a no-op
+(nothing new to record). Idempotency requires no extra dedup table.
+
+The `run.extended` entry is the point in the audit trail where the dynamic
+growth becomes attributable and verifiable. `pangolin verify` reads it to
+reconstruct the provenance graph covering both the original items and all
+spawned items — no separate verification path for dynamic runs.
+
+## The gate/respawn circle-back
+
+A pipeline gate is an ordinary work item whose executor returns a structured
+pass/fail signal in `outputs/gate.json`. The pattern phase reads that signal
+after the gate item reaches a terminal state.
+
+**Pass path.** Gate `done` + `outputs/gate.json` contains `{ "passed": true }`:
+the pattern emits the next stage. The gate item is sealed history; the next
+stage's items point back at the gate item via `depends_on`, so the engine knows
+to hold them only until the gate was `done` — which it already is.
+
+**Fail path (respawn).** Gate `done` but `{ "passed": false }`, or gate `failed`
+after retries: the pattern checks `respawnCount < maxRespawns` and, if allowed,
+emits a corrective sub-DAG. The corrective items carry `depends_on` pointing at
+the gate item. On the next tick, those corrective items enter as `pending` and
+the engine schedules them normally. When the corrective DAG completes, the
+pattern re-evaluates the gate stage — not by mutating old items, but by
+inspecting whether the *latest* gate-typed item on the run passed. A fresh pass
+advances the pipeline.
+
+**Respawn exhaustion.** If `respawnCount` reaches `maxRespawns`, the pattern
+emits nothing and the run settles with the gate stage in `failed`. Downstream
+stages are skip-cascaded by the engine's ordinary cascade phase; nothing in the
+pattern logic special-cases this.
+
+The circle-back is an **append**, not a loop. The failed branch is preserved as
+a permanent node in the graph. Auditors can read the full history: first attempt,
+gate failure, corrective run, second gate pass, pipeline advance. No state is
+overwritten.
+
+## The forward-arc-never-rewind invariant
+
+Every item in every pangolin-scale run graph obeys one structural rule:
+
+> **A `depends_on` edge may only point at an item whose id was present in the
+> run graph at the time the dependent item was created.**
+
+This means every edge points *backward* in time. The graph is always a DAG.
+Patterns are the only mechanism that adds items after submit, and `extendRun`
+enforces this rule at validation: any `depends_on` reference in a spawn
+directive that names an item id not yet in the run is rejected as an invalid
+forward arc.
+
+Why does this matter?
+
+- **The engine's dep-resolver is acyclic by assumption.** `computeNewlyReady`
+  iterates over items and checks `depends_on` against a terminal-status map. A
+  cycle would cause the resolver to spin forever. The invariant makes a cycle
+  structurally impossible.
+- **Replay is deterministic.** Because no item can depend on something that
+  doesn't exist yet, replaying the audit log in order always produces a valid
+  state: each `run.extended` entry's `depends_on` references are already present
+  from earlier entries or the original submit.
+- **Provenance closure is total.** `pangolin verify` walks `depends_on` backward
+  from every terminal item to the inputs. A forward arc would create a reference
+  to a not-yet-existing node — a gap in the closure. The invariant means verify's
+  walk always terminates at known inputs.
+- **Circle-backs are safe.** A pipeline respawn *feels* like going backward, but
+  the corrective items are new nodes appended after the failed gate. They depend
+  on the gate item (backward arc); nothing in the old branch depends on them
+  (which would be a forward arc into the future). The circle is semantic, not
+  structural.
+
+The invariant is checked mechanically in `validateRun` and re-checked in
+`extendRun` on every spawn. There is no runtime mode that relaxes it.
